{"type":"message","id":"40e1f90b","parentId":"4827da55","timestamp":"2026-04-14T03:45:39.598Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `system.route.ts` exports `router` as `default`. So `systemRoutes` is the `Router` from `system.route.ts`. The `system.route.ts` itself is a Router with paths like `/users`, `/roles`, etc. When mounted in `index.ts` as `router.use(systemRoutes)`, the full paths become `/users`, `/roles`, etc.\n\nBut wait, the `auth.route.ts` is `router.post('/auth/signin', ...)` and `router.use('/guests', guestsRoute)`. When mounted in `index.ts` as `router.use(authRoutes)`, the full paths become `/auth/signin` and `/guests`.\n \nI need to check what the base path for `systemRoutes` actually is. Looking at the `system.route.ts` imports and how it defines its routes like `/users` and `/roles`, when `authRoutes` is mounted at `/api/v1/auth`, the `/guests` endpoint would be at `/api/v1/guests`. But I'm not seeing a base path prefix in `system.route.ts` itself—let me trace through the index.ts to understand how these are being combined.","thinkingSignature":"5bb20212432cde622df75f3ce5ba6a7eb26ed931d2776201857fc61be7441fd3"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_rfvmv3hiw2ac_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport urllib.request\n# Try root\ntry:\n    resp = urllib.request.urlopen('http://localhost:5555/api/v1/', timeout=3)\n    print('Root:', resp.read().decode()[:100])\nexcept Exception as e:\n    print('Root error:', e)\n    \n# Try /api/v1/system\ntry:\n    resp = urllib.request.urlopen('http://localhost:5555/api/v1/system', timeout=3)\n    print('System:', resp.read().decode()[:100])\nexcept urllib.error.HTTPError as e:\n    print('System error:', e.code, e.read().decode()[:100])\nexcept Exception as e:\n    print('System error:', e)\n\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":132,"output":414,"cacheRead":90762,"cacheWrite":483,"total