{"type":"message","id":"bf75df72","parentId":"809f708c","timestamp":"2026-04-14T03:51:28.035Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The dist for roles.route.js looks correct. It has `router.get('/')` which should match `/api/v1/system/roles`.\n\nLet me check if the issue is with the `authMiddleware.auth()` function. Maybe it's NOT actually passing the request through properly - maybe it's calling `res.status().send()` instead of `next()`, which would prevent the request from reaching the route handlers.Wait - looking at the log again:\n```[32minfo[39m: [32madmin[39m[35mhttp[39m: [35m[0mGET /api/v1/system/roles [33m404[0m 12.416 ms - 2637[0m[39m```\n\n\nThe `admin` log is coming from AuthService, which means the auth middleware successfully decoded the JWT and found the user with the admin role. So the middleware is working - the problem must be that the request isn't reaching the actual route handler, or the route handler itself is returning a 404 for some reason.\n\nLet me trace through the auth middleware more carefully to see where the request is getting lost after authentication completes. The dist files look correct with all routes properly mounted, so let me try to actually hit an endpoint and see what's happening. I'm wondering if the issue is with how the auth middleware is chained or how the request is being passed through to the actual route handler.\n\nLooking at the execution flow: `auth()` runs first and passes successfully, then `systemRoutes` should handle the request, but something's returning 404 instead. Let me trace through what's actually happening after authentication completes.\n\nI think I found it—the `authMiddleware.auth()` function might be calling `res.status().send()` instead of `next()`, which would prevent the request from ever reaching the route handlers.","thinkingSignature":"4231b9f46961d63200c70381b8e40c96bf9ab79de7462985bc27ce16000af83e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_m1cz6ycvfw59_1","nam