{"type":"message","id":"9208c8b3","parentId":"505da987","timestamp":"2026-04-14T03:52:54.325Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `/api/v1/guests` endpoint (public) returns 200 OK. This means the routing to the auth route IS working.\n\nNow let me understand the route structure:\n- `/api/v1/auth/signin` → works (POST, auth route)\n- `/api/v1/guests` → works (GET, guests route)\n- `/api/v1/system/roles` → 404 (after auth)\n\nThe difference is:\n- `/api/v1/auth/signin`: matched by `router.use(auth_route_1.default)` which has `router.post('/auth/signin', ...)`\n- `/api/v1/guests`: matched by `router.use('/guests', guestsRoute)` inside auth.route.ts\n\n\n- `/api/v1/system/roles`: should be matched by `router.use(system_route_1.default)` after auth passes\n\nBut I'm noticing the route order in index.js matters here. The auth middleware runs first on all requests, then `systemRoutes` is mounted, so `/api/v1/system/roles` should definitely reach the system routes after auth completes. Let me trace through what's actually happening with the mount order and middleware chain.\n\nLooking at the auth route setup, it mounts `guestsRoute` at the `/guests` path and `DeviceRoute` at the `/devices` path. Since auth is a middleware itself rather than a final route handler, the system routes should still get registered after it completes. Let me verify the auth route actually exports as a router properly.","thinkingSignature":"9a13fd421095f54db94f5501142e353f6aeaba8ae13b633f295d9f264c550d9b"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_sm6zpozdxelz_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"head -3 /root/.openclaw/workspaces/ahv-driving-training-system/ahv-dtlx-backend/dist/presentation/api/v1/auth.route.js && echo \"---\" && cat /root/.openclaw/workspaces/ahv-driving-training-system/ahv-dtlx-backend/dist/presentation/api/v1/education.route.js | head -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":