{"type":"message","id":"ebdfc204","parentId":"777680eb","timestamp":"2026-04-14T04:00:55.968Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"403 Forbidden! Not 404. The auth middleware IS working - it returned 403 (forbidden) because no token was provided. This is `checkPermissions` returning 403 for not having a token.But wait - `/api/v1/auth/refetch-token` is in the auth.route, which should be BEFORE the auth middleware in index.ts. The auth middleware should NOT run for `/api/v1/auth/signin` and `/api/v1/auth/refetch-token`.\n\nLet me re-read index.ts:```ts\nrouter.use(authRoutes);  // Public routesrouter.use(authMiddleware.auth());  // Auth for all subsequent routesrouter.use(systemRoutes);```\n\n\nActually, the middleware order looks right - auth routes come first, then the auth middleware, then system routes. But the 403 on `/api/v1/auth/refetch-token` is puzzling. Either `authMiddleware.auth()` is running for all routes including auth ones, which would be wrong, or there's a separate middleware like `checkPermissions` being applied to auth routes that I'm not seeing. Let me check if `authMiddleware.auth()` is actually being applied globally instead of just to protected routes. I'm wondering if `checkPermissions` is also being applied globally somehow, since that would explain why the auth route itself is returning 403 when it should be publicly accessible. Let me trace through how the auth route is actually being registered to see if there's a middleware chain I'm missing.","thinkingSignature":"e0ed6b3cd4d0685a1b6205e0d33dd4b73e0f11bf9e7f5f35b7354846c9ba496c"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_grkcqlzdwksv_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"authMiddleware\\|checkPermissions\\|auth()\" /root/.openclaw/workspaces/ahv-driving-training-system/ahv-dtlx-backend/dist/presentation/api/v1/index.js"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":305,"output":353,"cacheRead"