{"type":"message","id":"d5c0b4f4","parentId":"de6f8b54","timestamp":"2026-04-14T04:02:53.713Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me try a different approach - I'll directly look at what routes are registered by modifying the running server. Actually, let me just try to add a debug console.log to the dist/index.js and see if it shows up when we make a request.But wait, I can't modify the running server's files and expect them to be reloaded (unless the server is watching files, which `node dist/server.js` doesn't by default).\n\nLet me try a completely different approach. Let me look at the `authMiddleware.auth()` function more carefully and see if there's a bug that causes it to NOT pass the request to the next handler in some cases.Looking at the auth middleware code again:\n\n\nSo the middleware wraps the authentication in a promise chain - it calls passport.authenticate, resolves the promise when verification succeeds, then calls next() to pass control to the next middleware. The catchAsync wrapper handles any errors that might slip through by passing them to next().","thinkingSignature":"9e3372b7c8ac18fba089de9cb339cd152016a23ab847b30d7de6291663068f77"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_en5junzpjafc_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /root/.openclaw/workspaces/ahv-driving-training-system/ahv-dtlx-backend/dist/common/utils/catchAsync.js"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":380,"output":243,"cacheRead":71778,"cacheWrite":320,"totalTokens":72721,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776139365499,"responseId":"062cef66bc738ae39289fd952799786c"}}
{"type":"message","id":"c7fabd2f","parentId":"d5c0b4f4","timestamp":"2026-04-14T04:02:53.965Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_en5junzpjafc_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\"use strict\";\nObject.defineProperty(exports, \"__esModule\", { value: true });\nconst catchAync = (fn) => {\n    return (req, res, next) => {\n        fn(req, res, next).catch(next);\n    };\n};\nexports.default = catchAync;\n//# sourceMappingURL=catchAsync.js.map"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":46,"aggregated":"\"use strict\";\nObject.defineProperty(exports, \"__esModule\", { value: true });\nconst catchAync = (fn) => {\n    return (req, res, next) => {\n        fn(req, res, next).catch(next);\n    };\n};\nexports.default = catchAync;\n//# sourceMappingURL=catchAsync.js.map","cwd":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776139373957}}
{"type":"message","id":"c309f257","parentId":"c7fabd2f","timestamp":"2026-04-14T04:03:10.166Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK let me think about this very carefully.\n\nThe `catchAsync` function:\n```jsconst catchAync = (fn) => {\n    return (req, res, next) => {\n        fn(req, res, next).catch(next);    };\n};```\n\nIt calls `fn(req, res, next)` which returns a Promise. If the promise rejects, `.catch(next)` passes the error to the error handler.\n\nNow `auth()`:```jsconst auth = (...allowedFields) => {\n    return catchAsync(async (req, res, next) => {\n        return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {            passport.authenticate('jwt', { session: false }, verifyCallback(req, res, resolve, reject, allowedFields))(req, res, next);        })            .then(() => next())            .catch((err) => next(err));\n    });};\n```\n\nSo when `auth` executes, it's an async function wrapped in `catchAsync` that returns a Promise. The Promise chain handles successful authentication by calling `next()` to advance, or catches any errors and passes them to the error handler. The `catchAsync` wrapper catches any errors that slip through the Promise chain.\n\nBut I'm wondering if there's a race condition where `next()` gets called multiple times, or if the auth middleware is somehow not completing properly and preventing the request from reaching the route handlers.\n\nLet me think about this differently. What if `passport.authenticate` itself is synchronous in some cases, and the promise resolves before Express has finished setting up the middleware chain? That could cause issues.\n\nActually, looking back at the logs for `/api/v1/auth/refetch-token`, the auth middleware is definitely running and completing successfully—I can see the token being decoded and the user being found. So the middleware itself is working fine. The problem must be that after auth passes, the subsequent routes aren't matching the request properly.\n\nLet me check what's happening in the system route itself. The middleware chain looks correct—`listenNotify` calls `next()` properly, and the roles router is mounted correctly. So the issue isn't there either. Maybe I need to add some debug logging directly to the server to see what's actually happening when those requests come through.\n\nActually, wait. The previous server instance was running with `ts-node/register` directly on the source files, but I just started a fresh one using the compiled `dist/server.js`. That's a meaningful difference. Let me verify which version is actually running right now.","thinkingSignature":"03e4d7d79d1acdb600b3099079dea8daab7072e378f579d5861af4ac98899655"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_24n9wjwdpi72_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /proc/$(ss -tlnp | grep 5555 | grep -oP 'pid=\\K[0-9]+')/cmdline | tr '\\0' ' '"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":181,"output":570,"cacheRead":72016,"cacheWrite":608,"totalTokens":73375,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776139373990,"responseId":"062cef6fa38772d1ad4ad23dc099fa9f"}}
