{"type":"message","id":"cd64f0d5","parentId":"b0b24c3b","timestamp":"2026-04-14T04:09:24.152Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"NOW we can see `[DEBUG system.route] ENTERED path=/system/roles url=/system/roles`. So the request IS reaching the system.route.js router! The path inside the system router is `/system/roles` (not `/system/roles` with baseUrl stripped... wait).Looking at the debug: `path=/system/roles url=/system/roles`. Inside the system router, the `path` is `/system/roles` because the system router was mounted at `/system` and the request is `/system/roles`. Wait, that doesn't sound right.Let me think. In index.js:\n```jsrouter.use(system_route_1.default);  // mounted at /system (since system.route has routes like /roles)```Actually, looking at system.route.js, it mounts its sub-routes directly:\n\n\n```jsrouter.use('/roles', listenNotify, roles_route_1.default);\n```So the system router has no prefix of its own. When the index router does `router.use('/system', system_route_1.default)` and the request is `/api/v1/system/roles`, the index router strips `/api/v1` and passes `/system/roles` to the system router. The system router should then match `/roles` against its `router.use('/roles', ...)`.\n\nBut the debug shows `path=/system/roles` INSIDE the system router. That means the system router is receiving the full path `/system/roles`, not just `/roles` — which suggests the index router isn't stripping the `/system` prefix before passing the request down. I'm realizing the path inside the system router should be `/roles` after the `/system` prefix is stripped, not `/system/roles` — unless something's wrong with how the router is being imported or mounted. Let me check the actual index.js code to see what's happening with the route mounting. I think I've found it—Express 5 changed how `app.use()` handles path prefixing, so when a router is mounted with a path prefix, that prefix gets prepended to all routes defined within it rather than just matching against it. So if `system.route.js` defines routes like `router.get('/')`, Express 5 would automatically serve those at `/system` instead of `/`. The issue is that the code expects routes to be matched at their defined paths, but they're actually being served with the mount prefix prepended.","thinkingSignature":"5ff32938b72f1bd3fe52df914bd9b51cf1837e8d96d5dfb2a754d78576d0b87b"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_salp4573mfje_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"node -e \"console.log(require('/root/.openclaw/workspaces/ahv-driving-training-system/ahv-dtlx-backend/node_modules/express/package.json').version)\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":181,"output":550,"cacheRead":80364,"cacheWrite":475,"totalTokens":81570,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776139750639,"responseId":"062cf0e8b89db30e3103dcc6ff0bc200"}}
