{"type":"message","id":"48f5c93e","parentId":"0a3ace65","timestamp":"2026-04-14T04:14:04.875Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Excellent! The API is mostly working! Here's the summary:\n\n✅ Working endpoints (200):\n- Auth: signin ✅\n- System: roles, agents, users/role ✅\n- Users: teachers, students, sales ✅\n- Education: courses, lessons, work-calendars, student-infos, exams ✅\n- Operation: vehicles, stadiums, payments ✅\n- Notification: notify-configs, notify-contents ✅\n- Public: guests ✅\n\n❌ Issues:\n1. `/api/v1/users/leads` → 400 Validation Error (likely needs specific params)\n\n\n2. `/api/v1/guests/register` → 401 Unauthorized (guests.register is actually protected!)\n\nI'm checking the guests route setup and it looks like the register endpoint should be public since it's just a POST without any auth middleware applied to it, so I need to dig into why it's returning 401.\n\nLooking at the auth middleware flow, when a POST request comes in without a token, passport should fail and reject the request, which would trigger the 401. But I'm realizing that guests.register might actually be protected by the auth middleware that's applied globally to all routes after the public ones. Let me trace through the route order to confirm whether guests.register is truly public or if it's getting caught by that global auth check.","thinkingSignature":"340fda58bb8f675f8d3e6e49793522c57cef4143b245b3c75214a522f17de051"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_plcxnnurpvlv_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"router\\.\\|'/\" /root/.openclaw/workspaces/ahv-driving-training-system/ahv-dtlx-backend/dist/modules/guests/guests.route.js | head -15"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":494,"output":335,"cacheRead":92604,"cacheWrite":1775,"totalTokens":95208,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":177614003376